    {
      "id": "WGzw4A4G_osOgRYVdtxMR",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 9237.8443592663,
      "y": -749.7507875037936,
      "width": 1435.081298828125,
      "height": 401.8875795791208,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "dashed",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b20",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1376395331,
      "version": 880,
      "versionNonce": 262335821,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1779560987490,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Collaborative Editing Approaches\n\n- OT (Operational Transformation)\nWe'll collect all of the edits to the document on a single server. \nFrom there, we can, in batches, transform each edit based on the edits that came before it\nOT requires a central server which can provide a final ordering of operations. \nThis allows us to scale to a small number of collaborators, but not an enormous number. \nOur non-functional requirements help us here. OT is also tricky to implement correctly and easy to get wrong.\n\n- CRDT (Conflict-free Replicated Data Type)\nCRDTs allow us to represent edits as a set of operations that can be applied in any order but still produce the exact same output.\nCRDTs are elegant in that they remove the need for a central server\n",
      "fontSize": 24.731543358715125,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Collaborative Editing Approaches\n\n- OT (Operational Transformation)\nWe'll collect all of the edits to the document on a single server. \nFrom there, we can, in batches, transform each edit based on the edits that came before it\nOT requires a central server which can provide a final ordering of operations. \nThis allows us to scale to a small number of collaborators, but not an enormous number. \nOur non-functional requirements help us here. OT is also tricky to implement correctly and easy to get wrong.\n\n- CRDT (Conflict-free Replicated Data Type)\nCRDTs allow us to represent edits as a set of operations that can be applied in any order but still produce the exact same output.\nCRDTs are elegant in that they remove the need for a central server\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
